I will always remember you Thatha ♥️

Singing for my Thatha was one of the most difficult songs to get through. I always knew the day would come, but I also knew I’d never be ready. This still hurts 💔 

I decided to share a vlog of this difficult week because grief is a part of life. It’s easy to share our highs but I feel it’s important to share our challenges. By doing so, we can encourage those experiencing a season of grief or sadness. And then, when we share our highs, we are proof that sadness is only one of many seasons in our life. There will be others, many of which are filled with joy ♥️

AND THAT’S ON SALE! 🙈 First time contestants are often shocked by the cost of custom couture piece. Custom pieces usually range between $1000-10,0000. 

I’m recent years I’ve heard of contestants spending as much as $18,000 on a couture gown. Those prices were always out of my budget. And, it’s okay if they’re out of yours too. 

I purchased my gowns resale when I competed and even used sites like @ebay, which allowed me to make payments. Nowadays a better option is to shop on @queenlyapp because they specialize in gowns and there’s no shortage of custom/couture styles you can shop there ☺️

Growing up in a low income household felt like a disadvantage. But, my perspective has changed. Invaluable skills I learned to survive now help me to thrive. 

I learned:
- the differences between wants and needs
- how to be content
- the value of a dollar
- possessions don’t equate to happiness
- hard work beats talent when talent doesn’t work

When I decided to break the cycle of generational poverty in college I learned:

- when you don’t have resources, be resourceful 
- how to budget
- pay yourself first
- build multiple income streams
- you don’t need a finance degree to be a successful investor
- plan for retirement in your 20s
- live below your means to avoid being a slave to your possessions 

…and a whole lot more. But all of that to say that each of us is born into circumstances beyond our control, but it is in our power to change them 💜

Your clothes were meant to be worn. 

The only reason you have a closet full of clothes and nothing to wear is because you haven’t built a wardrobe. 

If you’d like to have a more versatile wardrobe consider these things when you shop ⬇️⬇️⬇️

1.) Will I wear this piece at least 30 times?
2.) Does the color of this piece work with my existing clothes?
3.) Check garment seams and stitching for long wear quality. 
4.) Will I be excited to pull this piece when I’m getting dressed?
5.) Does this piece fit the aesthetic I’d like to create?
